                      FLETCH (FLASH Fetch)
                      February 1st, 1986
                      by Bob DeBula 



FLETCH is a convenience program for those of you who, like me, use 
the FLASH terminal program for your GENIE online sessions.  FLETCH 
stands for FLASH fetch.  One of the more time consuming tasks I 
found myself performing, when I found massive quantities of good 
Public Domain software in the ST roundtable libraries, was the "ST 
sitting" necessary to download it.  This was alleviated somewhat by 
a program I obtained from the ST libraries which had been written 
in Personal PASCAL.  This program freed me up from much of "dirty
work" of downloading multiple files by prompting me for my ID, 
password, and the files I wished to download.  To the author of 
that program I pay tribute for implementing a wonderful idea.  As 
I kept using this program I noticed several things, however: 1) I 
had to re-enter my ID, password, and the local GENIE phone number 
EVERY time I wanted to do some downloading. 2) the way the prompts 
worked for yes/no left me infinite room to make mistakes when 
keying in a long list of files to download. 3) Once I made a goof 
in keying in file names there was no way to correct it (once I 
replied "yes") short of re-running the whole thing and re-keying 
all the file names.  So I waited for a new program to appear in 
the PD libraries, and I waited.... SIGH, I guess I have to write 
it myself.  Well, I did and it is (you guessed it) FLETCH.

     Why FLETCH?  Well it is used with FLASH and it does fetches 
of files I want from the ST roundtable libraries (besides I like 
"personal" types of names and something like F2DLPGM1 just didn't 
seem right...I see enough of that at work in systems manuals).
Ergo, FLETCH has been born.  Is FLETCH full grown?  No way! It is 
still a software "rug-rat" (i.e.  it has some nasty bad habits and 
isn't nearly as useful as it will be after it grows up a bit).  I 
hope to have help in finding out the right things to "teach" 
FLETCH by getting mail from YOU the user of it.  If you want it to 
remain in the "ankle-bitting" stage and put up with it's nasty 
habits you need do nothing.  If, however, you want it improved, 
let me know what obnoxious bad habits it has (or good manners it 
lacks) and I MAY spend some time on it.  Due to a busy schedule 
(who doesn't have a "busy schedule"?) I can't commit myself to 
improving FLETCH on any set schedule (if at all).  Also I have my 
own predjudices on the way FLETCH grows up and may not incorporate 
your ideas.  This should NOT keep you from trying however (and if 
worse comes to worse you could always try adding the features you 
want yourself (this advice like "reading the manual" should only 
be taken as a true last resort)).

     FLETCH is written in GFA BASIC and I think that it points out 
the types of applications which can be written fairly quickly in 
what I consider to be a very "user friendly" language.  If I had 
done this in a "structured language" you might see it by Christmas 
1987 if I didn't lose interest first.  I will confess that FLETCH 
may well contain some pasta ("spagetti code"), whereas a version 
written in PASCAL or MODULA-2 probably wouldn't (read theoretically
couldn't but as long as there is some way to break the rules...).

Enough sermonizing, let me give you some of the gory details you 
need to know to install and use FLETCH.


Requirements:      FLASH from ANTIC Software  (every civilized 
                         person should have it, in my opinion;
                         Those who don't have an ST MAY have a
                         reasonably good excuse not to get it).

                   GFABASRO.PRG from Michtron (it is available for 
                                FREE from the Michtron libraries).

                   ARC.TTP if you don't have this it's in the ST 
                           roundtable libraries (although I'd like 
                           to know how you're reading this since 
                           it is ARCed and would probably appear
                           as something like "$#2342*&%@@3" 
                           anyhow).                    

                   ENOUGH MEMORY to run it (remember you're 
                                 running the GFA run only program,
                                 FLASH, and of course FLETCH 
                                 itself). Think this means a 520ST
                                 with TOS on ROM and a diet menu 
                                 of desk accessories.  I have 
                                 tested FLETCH on both a 520ST 
                                 color system and a 1040ST 
                                 monochrome system.

                   PATIENCE and UNDERSTANDING remember even "fast 
                                              Jack" didn't build 
                                              the first ST in a 
                                              day.  If you run out 
                                              of these remember 
                                              what you paid for 
                                              this program.



Installation:    1.) De-ARC the file.
                 2.) Copy the following files onto the disk and in 
                     the same folder (if you have a folder) as 
                     FLASH.PRG:
                                   
                     FLETCH.BAS   this is the program itself
                     FLETCH.CNF   names AUTO DO file
                     FLETCH.DAT   these are saved session 
                                  attributes (user ID, password,
                                  phone #, path, baud rate)
                     GFABASRO.PRG you'll have to get this from
                                  the Michtron libraries.


                 3.) FLETCH will create the following files when
                     it executes:

                     FLETCH.DO    the download DO file for FLASH
                     FLETCH.LOG   the log of the download session


Running FLETCH:   1.) Double click on GFABASIC.PRG then select 
                      FLETCH.BAS from the file selector input box 
                      which appears (it may be necessary to do 
                      some "directory digging" if you have FLASH 
                      in a folder).
                  2.) Enter the baud rate (default is 300).
                  3.) Enter your GENIE user ID, Password, local 
                      GENIE phone number, and the default path 
                      where you want the files you download to go.
                  4.) Enter the file number of the first file you 
                      want to download; then enter it's name; then
                      do it again a maximum of twenty times or hit
                      the "ESC" key or the return key in the next 
                      file number input column to stop entering 
                      files. If you wish to correct a previous 
                      entry press the "up arrow" key while in the 
                      file number column.  If you want to scroll
                      back down press the "down arrow" key while 
                      in the file number column.  If you hit 
                      return in the file number column or file 
                      name column without entering any data, input
                      will be terminated immediately.
                  5.) You will be asked if everything is O.K.
                      in an alert box. Reply "YES" if you are 
                      satisfied. "NO" means you start over at 
                      square one.
                  6.) You will be asked if you want to invoke 
                      FLASH now.  A "NO" reply will still save 
                      the FLASH "DO" file built by FLETCH.
                      This allows you to manually execute
                      "FLETCH.DO" from inside FLASH.
                  7.) If you execute FLASH and it fails for any 
                      reason you must check to see if the file
                      "OLDFLASH.CNF" exists.  If so: 1.) rename 
                      "FLASH.CNF" to "FLETCH.CNF" then 2.) rename 
                      "OLDFLASH.CNF" to "FLASH.CNF".


FEATURES I KNOW IT NEEDS:  1.) The ability to delete a line.
                           2.) Allow more than twenty files to be 
                               input (multiple pages).
                           3.) The ability to insert a line.
                           4.) Full support for the cursor, tab,
                               backspace, insert, and delete keys
                               in both columns (file # and name).
                           5.) The ability to re-show the file
                               numbers and names and allow them to
                               be re-edited after a "NO" reply 
                               from the alert box at the end of 
                               file input.


FEATURES THAT WOULD BE NICE:  1.) A receipt display of the file 
                                  select screen with columns 
                                  detailing number of blocks 
                                  downloaded, time needed to 
                                  download the file, & the cost
                                  for downloading the file.


